d in his creative thinking and identifies his use of the baroque as an important turn toward excess and hybrid forms. Beautifully illustrated with rare photographs, In Excess provides the most complete genealogy available of major shifts in this modern master’s theories and aesthetics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  a1920s, 1930s, avant-garde, que viva mexico, film, director, sergei eisenstein, soviet, leon trotsky, katherine anne porter, orson welles, modernity, postrevolutionary, revolution, walter benjamin, sexuality, bisexual, queer, lgbt, lgbtq, lgbtqia, mythology, politics, art, nonfiction, history, biography, excess, hybridity, genre, narrative, form, aesthetics, nationalism, maguey, fiesta, going all the way, sandunga.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226734163423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226734163/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles